      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i use the chunksize thing you mentioned, does that basically turn the pandas read into a generator object? and are there any specific risks of doing it that way, like if the memory usage still spikes unexpectedly or something? i'm worried about stuff \"leaking\" or just eating up everything i have available.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, using `chunksize` in `pandas.read_csv` returns an *iterator* object, which behaves much like a generator in that you process it piece by piece rather than loading everything at once. The primary risk is not usually a \"leak,\" but rather that if you start aggregating or storing the processed chunks into a single, large structure, you defeat the entire purpose and will reintroduce the memory issue. Always make sure your processing logic consumes each chunk immediately before moving to the next one.",
      "source": "target",
